<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>

	<h4> My first Javascript </h4>
	<p id="para"> This is the first paragraph </p>
	<button type="button" onclick='document.getElementById("para").innerHTML=Date()'>Click this</button>

<br>

	<p> In this case Javascript changes the value of the src (source) attribute of an image </p>

	<img id="myImage" src='https://scx2.b-cdn.net/gfx/news/hires/2018/2-dog.jpg' style="width: 100px">
	<br>

	<button onclick="document.getElementByI('myImage').src='https://scx2.b-cdn.net/gfx/news/hires/2018/2-dog.jpg'"> Dog </button>
	<button onclick="document.getElementByI('myImage').src='https://images.indianexpress.com/2019/04/cat_1200getty.jpg'"> Cat </button>

<br>

	<h2>Change Style</h2>

	<p id="demo"> Javascript can change the style of a HTML element.</p>

	<button type="button" onclick="document.getElementById('demo').style.fontSize='35px">Click Me!</button>
<br>
	
	<h2>What can javascript do?</h2>

	<button type="button" onclick="document.getElementById('demo').style.display='none'">Click Me!</button>

	<button type="button" onclick="document.getElementById('demo').style.display='none/block'">Click Me!</button>

<br>

<head>
	<script>
		function myFunction() {
			document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML="Paragraph changed.";
		}
	</script>
</head>

<h1>A Web Page</h1>
<p id="demo">A paragraph</p>
<button type="button" onclick="myFunction()">Try it</button>

<br>

<h2>External Javascript</h2>
<p id="demo">A paragraph</p>
<button type="button" onclick="myFunction()">Try it</button>

<p> (myFunction is stored in a n external file called "myScript.js")</p>

<script src="myScript.js"></script>

<br>

<h2>My first web page</h2>
<p>My first paragraph</p>

<p id="demo"></p>

<script>
	document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML=5+6;
</script>

